<p class="blurb" style="padding: 4px 0 6px 5px;">
<span style="color: #B1071C; font-weight: bold;">EXTRAS</span></p>

<p class="blurb" style="padding: 4px 0 6px 5px;">
<A HREF=" /free/2005/12/2005122201n.htm">Congress</A> approves final 2006 spending plan for student aid and NIH research <FONT SIZE="-2">(12/22/2005)</FONT>
</p>

<p class="blurb" style="padding: 4px 0 6px 5px;">
<A HREF=" /free/2005/12/2005122202n.htm">Pentagon budget</A> for basic research gets a trim, as legislation would cut nearly all federal spending by 1% <FONT SIZE="-2">(12/22/2005)</FONT>
</p>

<p class="blurb" style="padding: 4px 0 6px 5px;">
<A HREF=" /free/2005/12/2005122203n.htm">Katrina-damaged colleges</A> to get $200-million, as hurricane-relief bill clears final hurdle in Senate <FONT SIZE="-2">(12/22/2005)</FONT>
</p>

<p class="blurb" style="padding: 4px 0 6px 5px;">
<A HREF=" /free/2005/12/2005122204n.htm">Patriot Act gains</a> 5-week extension after new votes in Congress; talks to resume in 2006 on long-term renewal <FONT SIZE="-2">(12/22/2005)</FONT>
</p>



<p class="blurb" style="padding: 4px 0 6px 5px;">
<A HREF=" /daily/2005/12/2005122101n.htm">Senate passes vast bill</A> to cut billions in student loans, but some provisions favor borrowers' interests <FONT SIZE="-2">(12/21/2005)</FONT>
</p>

<p class="blurb" style="padding: 4px 0 6px 5px;">
<A HREF=" /daily/2005/12/2005122102n.htm">U. of California</A> retains contract to run Los Alamos lab, with 3 corporate partners <FONT SIZE="-2">(12/21/2005)</FONT>
</p>


<p class="blurb" style="padding: 4px 0 6px 5px;">
<A HREF=" /free/2005/12/2005122001n.htm">Federal judge rules,</A> in strongly worded opinion, that teaching intelligent design is unconstitutional </FONT> <FONT SIZE="-2">(12/20/2005)</FONT>
</p>



 

<div style="border:solid 1px #ba1127;background-color:#f0f0f0;padding:4px;font-size:.80em;margin-top:3px;margin-bottom:3px;">
<i>The Chronicle </i>is taking its annual holiday publishing break. No new articles will be posted for the next two weeks. The <A HREF="/chronicle/v52/5217guide.htm">complete contents</A> of our last issue, dated December 16, are available online. We will return with daily-news updates and a new print issue on Tuesday, January 3, 2006. Below is a selection of notable news, careers, and opinion articles, as well as some of our best online discussions, database projects, and most unusual news from the past year.
</div>

<table width="99%" cellpadding=0 cellspacing=5 border=0>
	<tr>
		<td width="55%" valign=top class="left_body" style="padding-right:8px;">


<H3 class="column_heds">Notable News Articles</H3>

<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT class="seclinks" style="margin-bottom:6px;">
<A HREF="/free/2005/12/breaknews.htm">Complete list</a><br>
</DIV>


<img src="/photos/v51/i29/at20050321.jpg" alt="Article Illustration" class="photo_front" width="195" height="130" border="0">
<A HREF="/weekly/v51/i29/29a01401.htm" CLASS="hed">CLOAK AND CLASSROOM</A>
<P CLASS="notes">
	A new, semi-secret government program provides scholarships to American social scientists who promise to work for U.S. intelligence agencies. Felix Moos (<i>above</i>), an anthropologist at the U. of Kansas, helped create a program to train intelligence analysts at universities.
	<br>
	<SPAN CLASS="photocredit">
		(Photograph by Eli Reichman)
	</SPAN>
</P>

<A HREF="/weekly/v51/i37/37a01201.htm" CLASS="hed">POETIC LICENSE</A>
<P CLASS="notes">
A librarian who ran an anonymous Web site alleging corruption in poetry contests has been unmasked, but the war of words continues.</P>


<!--Begin: discussion forums -->

<H3 class="column_heds">Career Articles</H3>
<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT class="seclinks" style="margin-bottom:6px;">
<A HREF="/free/2005/12/breakcareers.htm">Complete list</a><br>
</DIV>

<a href="/weekly/v51/i44/44c00301.htm" class="hed">BLOGGERS NEED NOT APPLY</a>
<p class="notes">Job seekers need to eliminate as many negatives as possible, and in most cases a blog turns out to be a negative.</p>

<a href="/weekly/v52/i02/02c00201.htm" class="hed">THEY SHOOT MESSENGERS, DON'T THEY?</a>
<p class="notes">If 'be careful what you say' is good advice for the job seeker, why is it so controversial to add the word 'online'?</p>


<H3 class="column_heds">Discussions</H3>
<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT class="seclinks" style="margin-bottom:6px;">
<A HREF="/free/2005/12/breakdiscussions.htm">Complete list</a><br>
</DIV>

<a href="http://chronicle.com/forums/colloquy/read.php? admview=1&f=1&i=5539&t=5539" class="hed">A LEFT WING ECHO-CHAMBER?</a>
<p class="notes">Is it appropriate for the American Library Association to take stands on political issues, such as a recent resolution calling for the United States to leave Iraq? <FONT SIZE="-2">(9/30/2005)</FONT></p>

<a href="http://chronicle.com/forums/colloquy/read.php? admview=1&f=1&i=5538&t=5538" class="hed">SHOULD LIBRARIANS GET TENURE?</a>
<p class="notes">Two librarians writing in <i>The Chronicle</i> take opposite positions about whether librarians need tenure. What do you think? <FONT SIZE="-2">(9/30/2005)</FONT></p>

<a href="/jobs/forums/list.php?f=20" class="hed">THE INTERVIEW PROCESS</a>
<p class="notes">A new forum where job seekers can share information about their conference and campus interviews. <FONT SIZE="-2">(12/18/2005)</FONT></p>

<a href="/jobs/forums/list.php?f=18" class="hed">THE ADMINISTRATIVE TRACK</a>
<p class="notes">In this forum, administrators talk about their job searches and share their on-the-job experiences. <FONT SIZE="-2">(12/2/2005)</FONT></p>

 <A HREF="/colloquy/2005/09/tulane/" class="hed">REBUILDING A UNIVERSITY IN KATRINA'S WAKE</A>
<p class="notes">Evacuating its campus was only the first challenge for Tulane University as Hurricane Katrina bore down on New Orleans.  Now the university -- like other institutions in the city -- faces the task of rebuilding while basic services are still unavailable and it has not been deemed safe to return. Tulane's president, Scott S. Cowen, says the university must reopen by next semester if it is to survive as a national research institution. How do you rebuild a university in a ghost town? <FONT SIZE="-2">(9/14/2005)</FONT></p>

<A HREF="/colloquy/2005/06/design/" class="hed">ATTENTION, ONLINE SHOPPERS FOR COLLEGES</A>
<p class="notes">High-school students these days are likely to shop for colleges online before they visit them in person. In response, colleges are developing Web sites with lots of bells and whistles. But can such splashy sites turn off prospective students? What is the best way to present an institution on the Web? <font size="-2">(6/9/2005)</font></p>
<!--End: discussion forums -->


<!--End: today's news column-->
		</td>
		<td width="45%" valign=top class="right_body">
<!-- Begin: From This Week's Chronicle -->

<H3 class="column_heds">Unusual News</H3>
<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT class="seclinks" style="margin-bottom:6px;">
<A HREF="/free/2005/12/breakunusual.htm">Complete list</a><br>
</DIV>


<img src="/photos/v52/i10/at-20051025.jpg" alt="Article Illustration" class="photo_front" width="195" height="155" border="0">
<A HREF="/weekly/v52/i10/10a01401.htm" CLASS="hed">MAYBE JUST TAXES</A>
<P class="notes">
Aging and death are not inevitable, claims a controversial biologist, and other scientists are paying attention. Aubrey de Grey (<i>above</i>) has iconoclastic theories about preventing and even reversing the aging process, and researchers are starting to take notice. 
	<br>
	<SPAN CLASS="photocredit">
		(Photograph by Peter Searle)
	</SPAN>
</P>

<A HREF="/weekly/v51/i19/19a04801.htm" CLASS="hed">LUMMOX NO MORE</A>
<P CLASS="notes">
How one man transformed himself from a hard-drinking, overweight college dropout to a thin, bike-obsessed professor at Southern Illinois University at Carbondale.</P>

<H3 class="column_heds">Notable Review Articles</H3>
<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT class="seclinks" style="margin-bottom:6px;">
<A HREF="/free/2005/12/breakreview.htm">Complete list</a><br>
</DIV>

<img src="/photos/v51/i23/cr20050211.jpg" alt="Article Illustration" class="photo_front" width="195" height="114" border="0">
<A HREF="/weekly/v51/i23/23b00601.htm" CLASS="hed">WONDROUS COMPLEXITY</A>
<P CLASS="notes">
	Those who think they see an end to scientific knowledge are shortsighted, writes Robert B. Laughlin, a Nobel Prize-winning professor of physics at Stanford University.
	<SPAN CLASS="photocredit"> (Illustration by Matt Manley)</SPAN>
</P>

<A HREF="/weekly/v51/i24/24b00701.htm" CLASS="hed">WAR WITHOUT END</A>
<P CLASS="notes">The military's use of depleted uranium and toxins such as Agent Orange has turned "smart wars" into eternal ecological battles, writes Rob Nixon, the Rachel Carson Professor of English at the University of Wisconsin at Madison.</P>

<H3 class="column_heds">Chronicle Databases</H3>
<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT class="seclinks" style="margin-bottom:6px;">
<A HREF="/free/2005/12/breakdata.htm">Complete list</a><br>
</DIV>
<A HREF="/free/v52/i11/11a02601.htm" class="hed">WHAT COLLEGE PRESIDENTS THINK</A>
<p class="notes">An exclusive <i>Chronicle</i> survey reveals college leaders' views of higher education, their jobs, and their lives. <span class="small">(11/4/2005)</span></p>	

<A HREF="/stats/990/" class="hed">EXECUTIVE COMPENSATION</A>
<p class="notes"><I>The Chronicle'</I>s annual survey of pay and benefits for presidents at <A HREF="/stats/990/">589 private institutions,</A> 1998-2004, and <A HREF="/stats/990/public.htm">139 public institutions,</A> 2004-6. <span class="small">(11/18/2005)</span></p>

